##95 confirmed! The Vice Minister of Health has been hit by an outbreak in Iran. Lost the Middle East?

Micro Signal China Business Journal

Function introduction, grow in step with Chinese enterprises, talk with business leaders, spread business ideals, serve business people, "China Business News" control of the absolute voice of Chinese business.

Iranian Deputy Health Minister Halić has been diagnosed with the new coronavirus, Reuters and local media reported Thursday. A spokesman for Iran's Health Ministry confirmed the news and said Halić was being treated, Reuters said.

All signs point to a growing epidemic in Iran, and the prospects for containing it appear to be faltering.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The day before his diagnosis, Halić was sweating during a press conference on the outbreak

Halić recorded a video after testing positive for the new coronavirus, according to several foreign and local Iranian media reports. In the video, he confirmed he was infected with the virus, but said "we will beat the virus" . Halić had been at the forefront of Iran's response to the outbreak, according to state media.

The day before Halić was diagnosed, he attended a news conference on Iranian state television about the new coronavirus outbreak.

The Daily Mail of London reported that Halić had been sweating profusely at the press conference, assuring the nation that the death toll was lower than feared.

Halić (left) wipes his face during a press conference on Jan. 24,2010

Not only that, he also denied the same day the Associated Press quoted Iran's semi-official IRNA news agency since February 13, the holy city of Qom, Iran, 50 people have died of COVID-19 pneumonia theory.

More than 250 people have been quarantined in the city, Qom Ahmad, a local lawmaker, was quoted as saying by IRNA news agency. The official also said the earliest time that 50 people had died could be dated back to February 13.

The cumulative number of confirmed cases in Iran has increased to 95

Iran's Ministry of Health, Public Relations and Information Center Director Jahanpur 25, disclosed that 34 new cases of pneumonia confirmed in Iran, an additional 3 deaths. Sixteen are from Qom and nine are from Tehran. Most confirmed cases have a history of exposure to coombs.

As of noon on the 25th, a total of 95 cases of new pneumonia and 15 deaths have been confirmed in Iran. On the 24th, many countries in the Middle East confirmed the first case of new pneumonia imported from Iran. Currently, six land-based neighbours, with the exception of Azerbaijan, have closed their borders with Iran.

So far, the Iranian government has closed schools in most parts of the country and suspended football matches. Theater and other venues will also be suspended. The Iranian government has begun routine sanitation work on the Tehran Metro and the city's public transport vehicles.

On the 23rd local time, Iranian President Rohani attended a cabinet meeting, said Tehran will use military force to control the epidemic, as far as possible to reduce losses. According to Press TV, Rohani also issued an order on the same day asking the Iranian health minister, Saeed Namaki, to lead the establishment of a national epidemic prevention and Control Headquarters.

Experts worry about losing the Middle East

Health experts have expressed concern about the situation in Iran, saying the Middle East is "the best place" to start a pandemic because of the frequent movement of pilgrims and workers between countries.

As of 25th, the number of confirmed cases of new coronavirus pneumonia in the Middle East has increased to nine: 95 in Iran, 17 in Bahrain, 13 in the United Arab Emirates, 8 in Kuwait, 6 in Israel, 5 in Iraq, 4 in Oman, 1 in Afghanistan and 1 in Lebanon.

The outbreak has led to soaring prices for hospital masks in countries including Iran, Iraq, Lebanon and Afghanistan, some of which can cost up to 30 times the normal price.

More worrying for experts, however, is the ability of countries in the Middle East to respond to the virus. Health Systems, particularly in Syria, Iraq, Afghanistan and Yemen, have been damaged by civil war or years of unrest.

"are countries in the Middle East Ready? " said Dr. Montaser Bilbisi, a Jordanian infectious disease expert. "Frankly, I don't [ see ] the level of preparedness and vigilance of China or other countries, or even some personal protective equipment, " he said, he has yet to see a fully protective suit, so the risk of infection among health care workers is very high.
